Summary:
Clang static analysis does not warn about erroneous calls to -dealloc.

Steps to Reproduce:
Add the following class definition to a project, then run build and analyse:

@interface MyClass : NSObject {
	NSObject *foo;
}
@property (retain) NSObject *foo;
@end

@implementation MyClass
@synthesize foo;

- (void) dealloc {
	[foo dealloc]; // WRONG, should be [foo release]
	[super dealloc];
}
@end

Expected Results:
A warning about the erroneous call to [foo dealloc]

Actual Results:
Clean build-and-analyse with no warnings. 

Regression:
Same result on Xcode 3.2.6 (LLVM 1.7).

Notes:
Any call to -dealloc except [suoer dealloc] within a subclass's own dealloc implementation is highly suspicious. This is quite an easy error to make and quite hard to track down, so the warning would be particularly valuable.

Duplicates rdar://9402423

Summary: NSDictionary with a NSNumber behaves differently on the iPad/iPhone device than it does on the simulator.

Steps to Reproduce:

    NSMutableDictionary *dict = [NSMutableDictionary dictionary];
    [dict setObject:@"Test 1" forKey:[NSNumber numberWithDouble:-1.0]];
    [dict setObject:@"Test 2" forKey:[NSNumber numberWithDouble:-2.0]];
    NSString *result = [dict objectForKey:[NSNumber numberWithInt:-1]];

Expected Results:

I'd expect result == @"Test 1", even on the device. I'd also expect the simulator and device to behave the same.

Actual Results:

On the device, result == nil. In the simulator, result == @"Test 1".

Regression:

Notes:

It does work fine with positive numbers and when creating the two NSNumbers the same way (e.g. both with numberWithInt).

I think the static analyzer should show warnings about calls to dealloc, that aren't [super dealloc] from the subclass' -dealloc method. 

For example the following should obviously never occur under Objective-C memory management rules:

- (void)dealloc {
    [foo dealloc];
    [super dealloc];
}

The analyzer should warn about this so we can correct it to:

- (void)dealloc {
    [foo release];
    [super dealloc];
}

After spending a while tracking down a crash, caused by mistakingly calling dealloc instead of release, this ability would greatly improve the debugging of such cases in apps, and make some much more stable.

