Summary:
When SecTrustEvaluate is called for a SecTrustRef that contains an EV candidate
certificate, a policy to fetch CRLs and OCSP from the cache only, action data to
check revocation per certificate, and a set of anchors set via
SecTrustSetAnchorCertificates, it's possible for a CFArrayRef of EV anchor
certificates to be leaked.

Steps to Reproduce:
Create a SecPolicyRef for CRLs (default is network fetching disabled)
Create a SecPolicyRef for OCSP, with network fetching disabled
Create a SecPolicyRef for basic SSL validation
Create a SecCertificateRef for an end-entity certificate that chains to an EV root
Create a SecTrustRef for the certificate and policies
Add a list of trusted anchors via SecTrustSetAnchorCertificates[/Only]
Set the policy ACTION_DATA to include CSSM_TP_ACTION_REQUIRE_REV_PER_CERT
Call SecTrustEvaluate()

Expected Results:
Valgrind reports no memory errors

Actual Results:
Valgrind reports a memory leak in the call to SecTrustEvaluate

Regression:

Notes:

The Valgrind backtrace is:

Leak_DefinitelyLost
256 bytes in 1 blocks are definitely lost in loss record 1,623 of 1,882
  realloc (mp/valgrind-src/valgrind-memcheck/valgrind/coregrind/m_replacemalloc/vg_replace_malloc.c:525)
  DefaultAllocator::realloc(void*, unsigned long)
  Security::CssmAllocatorMemoryFunctions::relayRealloc(void*, unsigned long, void*)
  Security::CssmMemoryFunctions::realloc(void*, unsigned long) const
  Security::CssmMemoryFunctionsAllocator::realloc(void*, unsigned long)
  Attachment::upcallRealloc(long, void*, unsigned int)
  Security::PluginSession::realloc(void*, unsigned long)
  DecodedExtensions::addExtension(cssm_data const&, bool, void*, bool, SecAsn1Template_struct const*, cssm_data const*)
  DecodedExtensions::decodeFromNss(NSS_CertExtension**)
  DecodedCert::DecodedCert(AppleX509CLSession&, Security::CssmData const&)
  AppleX509CLSession::CertGetFirstFieldValue(Security::CssmData const&, Security::CssmData const&, unsigned int&, cssm_data*&)
  cssm_CertGetFirstFieldValue(long, cssm_data const*, cssm_data const*, long*, unsigned int*, cssm_data**)
  CSSM_CL_CertGetFirstFieldValue
  allowedEVRootsForLeafCertificate
  Security::KeychainCore::Trust::evaluate()
  SecTrustEvaluate

The leak can clearly be seen in http://www.opensource.apple.com/source/libsecurity_keychain/libsecurity_keychain-40768/lib/Trust.cpp, reproduced in part below:

void Trust::evaluate(bool disableEV)
{
	bool isEVCandidate=false;
	// begin evaluation block with stack-based mutex
	{
	StLock<Mutex>_(mMutex);
	// if we have evaluated before, release prior result
	clearResults();
	
	// determine whether the leaf certificate is an EV candidate
*1	CFArrayRef allowedAnchors = allowedEVRootsForLeafCertificate(mCerts);
	CFArrayRef filteredCerts = NULL;
*2	isEVCandidate = (allowedAnchors && !disableEV) ? true : false;
	if (isEVCandidate) {
		secdebug("evTrust", "Trust::evaluate() certificate is EV candidate");
		filteredCerts = potentialEVChainWithCertificates(mCerts);
	} else {
		if (mCerts) {
			filteredCerts = CFArrayCreateMutableCopy(NULL, 0, mCerts);
		}
*3		if (mAnchors) {
*4			allowedAnchors = CFArrayCreateMutableCopy(NULL, 0, mAnchors);
		}
	}

*1: Because the SecCertificateRef passed in is an EV candidate, allowedAnchors is a valid CFArrayRef of one or more EV root certificates
*2: If disableEV is true, isEVCandidate will be set to false
*3: Because SecTrustSetAnchorCertificates() was called, mAnchors will be non-null
*4: At this point, the original allowedAnchors from *1 is leaked, replaced with a copy of the mAnchors

As far as I can tell from my cursory search, there is only one place where disableEV will be set to true, which is at the end of Trust::evaluate()

	if (isEVCandidate && mResult == kSecTrustResultRecoverableTrustFailure &&
		isRevocationServerMetaError(mTpReturn)) {
		// re-do the evaluation, this time disabling EV
		evaluate(true);
	}

Because the certificate is an EV candidate certificate, the OCSP policy specified by the user will be updated to require OCSP if a responder is specified. However, because network fetching is explicitly disabled, the OCSP status will return CSSMERR_APPLETP_OCSP_UNAVAILABLE as a result. Such a result will cause isRevocationServerMetaError to return true. When this happens, evaluate() will be called again, which is where the leak happens.

CFReleasing and nil'ing allowedAnchors if !isEVCandidate, prior to any possible copy of mAnchors, seems like an appropriate fix, but has not been tested.

