Notes:
I ran into this when I wrote a -(CGFloat)[Vector2D length]. When called on an id pointer, the compiler chooses to compile that as if it was a call to -(NSUInteger)[NSData length], and does math on that int; not by casting, but by interpreting the bits as an int. This is fine, and not unexpected given that this is ObjC. However, emitting the int math code and not warning about it led to quite a bit of debugging before finding out why stuff went wrong.

Output of program is:
2011-01-22 19:56:10.907 lengthTest[42053:a0f] Hello, World! 4294971392.000000
because the compiler interprets the bits in the float as an int and does math on that (addq instead of addsd).

