10-Oct-2010 01:07 AM Daniel Svensson:
Summary:
Using FindNextComponent causes SIGPIPE to be not blocked any longer in the whole process. This causes problems when a unix socket is unexpectedly closed while writing.

Steps to Reproduce:
Build the following C-code by using:
gcc -pthread -o sigpipetest sigpipe.c -framework CoreServices -framework CoreAudio

The code:
#include <signal.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdio.h>

#include <CoreServices/CoreServices.h>
#include <AudioUnit/AudioUnit.h>

int break_the_pipe ()
{
	ComponentDescription desc;

	desc.componentType = kAudioUnitType_Output;
	desc.componentSubType = kAudioUnitSubType_DefaultOutput;
	desc.componentManufacturer = kAudioUnitManufacturer_Apple;
	desc.componentFlags = 0;
	desc.componentFlagsMask = 0;

	FindNextComponent (NULL, &desc);
}


int main (int argc, char **argv)
{
	sigset_t signals, old;

	sigemptyset(&signals);
	sigaddset (&signals, SIGPIPE);
	pthread_sigmask (SIG_BLOCK, &signals, &old);

	break_the_pipe ();

	while (1) {
		printf ("main loop lives!\n");
		sleep (1);
	}

	return 0;
}

Expected Results:
The code above should properly block SIGPIPE.

Actual Results:
When killing the process with SIGPIPE it exits.

Regression:
I belive this was introduced in 10.6 but I'm not sure. We haven't had any problems with OS X since it was first supported around 2004.

Notes:
The code that used FindNextComponent now uses the new AudioComponentFindNext instead and works as expected, but this requires me to depend on 10.6 and thus leaving users with older versions of the OS out of luck.

